How It Works
The user enters a request in the Streamlit chat interface.
The OpenAI model analyzes the request.
The MCP client discovers the available tools exposed by the local MCP server.
The AI selects the appropriate tool(s).
The MCP server executes the requested operations.
Results are returned to the AI and displayed in the chat interface.
Example Prompts
Create a file named notes.txt with today's meeting notes.
Search my saved notes for "Python".
Check the weather in Pune.
Find the latest AI news.
Summarize the latest AI news and save it as ai_report.txt.
Create a folder called Projects and move report.txt into it.
Environment Variables

Create a .env file:

OPENAI_API_KEY=your_openai_api_key
TAVILY_API_KEY=your_tavily_api_key

Note: I initially used a Google App Password instead of a Tavily API key, which prevented the live web search feature from returning current information. Replacing it with a valid Tavily API key resolved the issue.

